ntributor-link" rel="author" href="../contributor/luke-darby" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.0.0.0:$author.1:$0.2">Luke Darby</a></div></div><time class="publish-date" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.0.0.1">October 16, 2015 9:00 am</time></div></div><div class="col col-sm-5" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1"><div class="social-share-top" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0"><div class="component-social-share default" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0"><div class="share-item facebook" data-href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fsilent-movie-roots-horror-film-genres&amp;t=The%20Silent-Movie%20Roots%20of%20Your%20Favorite%20Horror%20Film%20Genres" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fsilent-movie-roots-horror-film-genres&amp;t=The%20Silent-Movie%20Roots%20of%20Your%20Favorite%20Horror%20Film%20Genres" target="_blank" aria-label="Facebook" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0"><span class="icon" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0.0"></span><span class="label" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0.1">Facebook</span></a></div><div class="share-item twitter" data-href="https://twitter.com/share?text=The%20Silent-Movie%20Roots%20of%20Your%20Favorite%20Horror%20Film%20Genres&amp;via=GQMagazine&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fsilent-movie-roots-horror-film-genres" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-twitter"><a href="https://twitter.com/share?text=The%20Silent-Movie%20Roots%20of%20Your%20Favorite%20Horror%20Film%20Genres&amp;via=GQMagazine&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fsilent-movie-roots-horror-film-genres" target="_blank" aria-label="Twitter" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-twitter.0"><span class="icon" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-twitter.0.0"></span><span class="label" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-twitter.0.1">Twitter</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="body-text" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4"><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.0">As Halloween season starts to ramp up, cinemas are furnishing their theaters with assorted terrors&#x2014;and among them is Guillermo Del Toro&apos;s <em>Crimson Peak</em>, which opens this week. Set in a spooky, labyrinthine English manor, <em>Crimson Peak</em> looks in a lot of ways like a super-glossy, modern take on a 119-year-old movie about the devil in a castle. It may look dated as hell now, but <em>Le Manoir du Diable</em> (1896), a three-minute film made by father of early cinema George Melies, is the first in a long, long line of a genre that people love to hate.</p><div class="embed figure" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.1"><figure class="embedded-video"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/OPmKaz3Quzo" height="" width=""></iframe></figure></div><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.2">Most modern horror movies can trace their influences back to the earliest decades of cinema. Horror wasn&apos;t considered its own genre until the 1930s, when Universal Studios began making insane money off of monster movies like <em>Dracula</em> (1931). But <em>Dracula</em> wasn&apos;t even the first Dracula. <em>Nosferatu</em> (1922), probably the best-known silent film today, is an unlicensed rip-off of Bram Stoker&apos;s novel.</p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.3">Since <em>Le Manoir du Diable</em>, the haunted house movie has reappeared as <em>Paranormal Activity</em> (2007), <em>The Shining</em> (1980), and <em>The Haunting</em> (1963), and more&#x2014;even the original <em>Alien</em> (1979), if you&apos;re open to interpretation. And now <em>Crimson Peak</em>. So to celebrate Halloween, and Del Toro being a horror movie nerd, we traced the lineage of the most common horror tropes back to their (mostly) silent sources.</p><div class="embed hr" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.5"><hr></div><div class="embed h2" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.6"><h2><strong>The mad doctor</strong></h2></div><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.7">A lot of the standards of horror movies were already established in horror novels, many from the Victorian era. And lots of Victorian writers were worried about the dangerous amorality of science.</p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.8">Which brings us to <em>The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde</em> by Robert Louis Stevenson. Since the story has been parodied to death and even made into a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pdasaGIwmmo"><em>Wishbone</em></a> <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pdasaGIwmmo">episode</a>, we&apos;ll spare you the synopsis. But the 1920 <em>Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde</em> starring John Barrymore remains the most iconic version, even overshadowing another version with the same name that came out in the same year.</p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.9">Maybe we haven&apos;t lost that distrust of science, or maybe the deranged scientist just makes for a really convenient storytelling device. It gives a writer a reason <em>why</em> there are giant ants attacking a high school, or sentient hurricanes following you. Throughout movie history, mad scientists have merged with bugs (<em>The Fly</em>, 1958), stolen people&apos;s faces (<em>Eyes Without a Face</em>, 1960), brought the dead back to life (<em>The Reanimator</em>, 1985), and built hunky blond sex toys (<em>The Rocky Horror Picture Show</em>, 1975).</p><div class="embed figure" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.a"><figure class="embedded-video"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/B8i0U3nUi8E" height="" width=""></iframe></figure></div><div class="embed h2" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.b"><h2><strong>The carnival</strong></h2></div><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.c">To more esoteric film nerds, <em>The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari</em> (1920) is the best example of German expressionism, where surreal landscapes reflect the characters&apos; mental states. To everyone else, it&apos;s what inspired Tim Burton back in his Beetlejuice days.</p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.d">It&apos;s also the most influential spooky carnival in cinema. When a fair opens in the village of Holstenwall, the deranged Dr. Caligari shows off his hypnotized Somnambulist, kept in the titular cabinet. Along with <em>Nosferatu</em>, <em>The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari</em>, with its murderous sleep-walker, is probably the best-known movie on this list.</p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.e">Later horror movies that depend on the evil carnival include the psychedelic <em>Santa Sangre</em> (1989), the film version of Ray Bradbury&apos;s classic <em>Something Wicked This Way Comes</em> (1983), and the low-budget and <em>legitimately terrifying Carnival of Souls</em> (1962). But a natural spin-off of the creepy carnival is the evil clown clich&#xE9;, which didn&apos;t get a lot of traction until the late &apos;80s. So if you were lucky enough to see <em>It</em> (1990), you can thank the good doctor.</p><div class="embed figure" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.f"><figure class="embedded-video"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/AP3WDQXkJq4" height="" width=""></iframe></figure></div><div class="embed h2" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.g"><h2><strong>The slasher</strong></h2></div><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.h">The slasher flick is the workhorse of horror movies. In a lot of ways, it&apos;s the oldest story anyone knows: It&apos;s the Boogeyman, the Someone Bad, and it&apos;s coming for you. The killer can be supernatural like Freddy Kruger, theoretically human (if unkillable) like Michael Myers, or just some punk kids like Matthew Lillard. Slashers hit peak popularity in the &apos;80s, after the huge success of <em>Halloween</em> (1978). Wes Craven has probably done more to keep this subgenre afloat than anyone else, and managed to single-handedly revive it with <em>Scream</em> (1996), which managed to be scary, funny or meta, depending largely on how old you were when you saw it.</p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.i">The grand-daddy of all other slashers is Hitchcock&apos;s <em>Psycho</em> (1960), but in 1932, <em>Thirteen Women</em> gave us our first clear-cut slasher, and our first movie about murdered sorority girls. After offing each former sorority member, the killer crosses out her yearbook picture, paving the way for low budget, tacky college slashers for decades. So <em>Sorority Row</em> (2009) was actually part of a proud cinematic tradition&#x2014;and not just a lazy vehicle for T&amp;A.</p><div class="embed figure" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.j"><figure class="embedded-video"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/2j3MSJvmDBg" height="" width=""></iframe></figure></div><div class="embed h2" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.k"><h2><strong>The horror comedy</strong></h2></div><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.l">You&apos;re probably more familiar with D.W. Griffith as the director of <em>Birth of a Nation</em> (1915), which was a huge technological breakthrough in movie-making and the best PR anyone&apos;s ever given the KKK. Along with that dubious honor, Griffith is also responsible for sparking a wave of horror comedy in the 1920s. <em>One Exciting Night</em> (1922), despite having a name that suggests a honeymoon-centric rom-com, was so popular that it set off a wave of copycats, like the original <em>The Cat and the Canary</em> (1927), which was remade <em>five times</em>.</p><div class="embed figure" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.m"><figure class="embedded-video"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/jz6ClE2SZoY" height="" width=""></iframe></figure></div><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.n">Today horror comedies tend to satirize scary movie cliches, like <em>Cabin in the Woods</em> (2012) or <em>Shaun of the Dead</em> (2004). But film&apos;s early days, before there was enough to satirize, there was just black comedy, usually screwball and usually with an off-balance mix of horror and humor.</p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.o">The horror-comedy hybrid makes more sense in many cases than outright horror. There&apos;s something intrinsically absurd about watching a movie just to be made afraid, to become anxious and stressed about the fate of fictional characters. But the comedy allows you to decompress while swinging from one high to another. Sometimes you need that breath before you can sink deeper and stare down Cujo one more time.</p><div class="embed hr" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.p"><hr></div><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.q">Read More:</p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.r"><a href="scariest-horror-movies-ever">Scared S#!tless: 52 Movies That Will Make Every Man Scream Like a Little Girl</a></p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.s"><a href="goodnight-mommy-scariest-movie-trailer">The Scariest Movie of All Time Is Actually Just This Trailer for a Scary Movie</a></p><p data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.4.t"><a href="taissa-farmiga-the-final-girls-faces-of-fear">Taissa Farmiga of &#x200B;<em>The Final Girls</em>&#x200B; Shows Off Her Scary Horror Faces</a></p></div><div class="grid" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5"><div class="row" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0"><div class="col col-sm-15" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0"><div class="component-topics" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0"><ul data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0"><li data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-0"><a href="../search?tags=Entertainment" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-0.0">Entertainment</a></li><li data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-1"><a href="../search?tags=Movies" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-1.0">Movies</a></li><li data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-2"><a href="../search?tags=Guillermo%2520Del%2520Toro" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-2.0">Guillermo Del Toro</a></li><li data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-3"><a href="../search?tags=Crimson%2520Peak" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-3.0">Crimson Peak</a></li></ul></div></div><div class="col col-sm-5" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.1"><div class="social-share-bottom" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0"><div class="component-social-share default" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0"><div class="share-item facebook" data-href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fsilent-movie-roots-horror-film-genres&amp;t=The%20Silent-Movie%20Roots%20of%20Your%20Favorite%20Horror%20Film%20Genres" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fsilent-movie-roots-horror-film-genres&amp;t=The%20Silent-Movie%20Roots%20of%20Your%20Favorite%20Horror%20Film%20Genres" target="_blank" aria-label="Facebook" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0"><span class="icon" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0.0"></span><span class="label" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0.1">Facebook</span></a></div><div class="share-item twitter" data-href="https://twitter.com/share?text=The%20Silent-Movie%20Roots%20of%20Your%20Favorite%20Horror%20Film%20Genres&amp;via=GQMagazine&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fsilent-movie-roots-horror-film-genres" data-reactid=".11tygazjs3k.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-ite